 #
 # 1180 : Prinz Mochihito's Rebellion
 #

 bm_pmrta1180:0 "EXTRA - Prinz Mochihito's Rebellion"
 bm_pmrta1180_desc:0 "Nach den Bürgerkriegen von Hogen (1156) und Heiji (1159) dominierte der Taira-Clan (Heishi) den kaiserlichen Hof. Taira no Kiyomori wurde zum Daijo Daijin, dem höchsten Kanzler des Reiches, ernannt, und sein Clan besaß so viele Lehen, dass ein Familienmitglied sagte: "Wer nicht zum Taira-Clan gehört, sollte kein echter Adliger sein." Der Konflikt zwischen Kiyomori und dem pensionierten Kaiser Go-Shirakawa wurde jedoch Ende der 1170er Jahre ernst und einige Anti-Taira-Fraktionen begannen zu planen."

 bm_pmrta1180_prince_mochihito:0 "Mochihito"
 bm_pmrta1180_prince_mochihito_desc:0 "Prince Mochihito\n1151-1180\n\nPrince of Emperor Go-Shirakawa. At the recommendation of Minamoto no Yorimasa, Mochihito sent a message by the name of the Prince to members of the Minamoto clan.\n\nAlthough Mochihito himself raised his forces, he lost and died eventually."
 bm_pmrta1180_taira_kiyomori:0 "Kiyomori"
 bm_pmrta1180_taira_kiyomori_desc:0 "Taira no Kiyomori\n1118-1181\n\nHead of the Taira clan. After the Hōgen and Heiji rebellion, his clan rose rapidly by keeping the Minamoto clan in check. Kiyomori became Daijō-daijin and established power by the Taira clan. As he married his daughter Tokuko to Emperor Takakura, and the Taira clan monopolized officials of the government, they extremely flourished.\n\nIn his later years, however, Kiyomori got caught up in rising ups of the Minamoto clan and died from fever disease. Also, he is known for encouraging trading between Japan and the Song Dynasty of China."
 bm_pmrta1180_taira_munemori:0 "Munemori"
 bm_pmrta1180_taira_munemori_desc:0 "Taira no Munemori\n1147-1185\n\nA child of Taira no Kiyomori. Munemori succeeded to Kiyomori after his death. Munemori led the Taira clan and fought against the Minamoto clan risen here and there.\n\nAfter the Battle of Dan-no-Ura, Munemori was caught by Minamoto no Yoshitsune and executed."
 bm_pmrta1180_minamoto_yorimasa:0 "Yorimasa"
 bm_pmrta1180_minamoto_yorimasa_desc:0 "Minamoto no Yorimasa\n1104-1180\n\nYorimasa recommended Prince Mochihito to defeat the Taira clan, and Yorimasa himself rose together, only lost and committed suicide.\n\nYorimasa was a master of archery and also known as a poet."
 bm_pmrta1180_minamoto_yoritomo:0 "Yoritomo"
 bm_pmrta1180_minamoto_yoritomo_desc:0 "Minamoto no Yoritomo\n1147-1199\n\nThe first Shogun of the Minamoto Shogunate. Although Yoritomo lost at the Heiji rebellion and was banished to Izu, he accepted a request of Prince Mochihito that Yoritomo uprose his army.\n\nAs Yoritomo extended his power based in Kamakura, he defeated Minamoto no Yoshinaka, the Taira clan, and Northern Fujiwara. Finally, Yoritomo subdued Japan. He introduced Shugo and Jitō system as fundamentals of the Samurai government. Then he became a Shogun and established his Shogunate."
 bm_pmrta1180_minamoto_yoshinaka:0 "Yoshinaka"
 bm_pmrta1180_minamoto_yoshinaka_desc:0 "Minamoto no Yoshinaka\n1154-1184\n\nAlso known as Kiso Yoshinaka. Yoshinaka accepted Prince Mochihito's request to raise at Kiso.\n\nYoshinaka defeated the Taira clan at Kurikara Pass, then he occupied Kyoto. Although the Japanese world was divided by three powers; Minamoto no Yoritomo, Yoshinaka, and the Taira clan, Yoshinaka was opposed to ex-Emperor Go-Shirakawa. Finally, Yoshinaka lost and died by Minamoto no Noriyori and Yoshitsune ordered by Yoritomo."
 bm_pmrta1180_fujiwara_hidehira:0 "Hidehira"
 bm_pmrta1180_fujiwara_hidehira_desc:0 "Fujiwara no Hidehira\n1122-1187\n\nHidehira was the third generation of North Fujiwara, leading to the heyday of them.\n\nAt the time of the uprising of Minamoto no Yoritomo, Hidehira was ordered by the Taira clan to defeat Yoritomo but Hidehira acted nothing. After the ruin of the Taira clan, he gave shelter to Minamoto no Yoshitsune who was opposing Yoritomo.\n\nHidehira's body is rested at Chūson-ji Konjiki-dō."
 bm_pmrta1180_kikuchi_takanao:0 "Takanao"
 bm_pmrta1180_kikuchi_takanao_desc:0 "Kikuchi Takanao\nYear of birth and death unknown\n\nSamurai from Higo. Takanao uprose opposing to control of Kyushu by the Taira clan.\n\nOnce Takanao successfully advanced to Dazaifu, eventually surrendered and allied to the Taira side. Later he accompanied Emperor Antoku, who had escaped to Dazaifu."
 bm_pmrta1180_kono_michikiyo:0 "Michikiyo"
 bm_pmrta1180_kono_michikiyo_desc:0 "Kono Michikiyo\n?-1181\n\nSamurai from Iyo. Michikiyo uprose in concert with Minamoto no Yoritomo together with Michikiyo's child, Kono Michinobu.\n\nOnce Michikiyo controlled Iyo country, eventually he died by the attack of the Taira allies. Leading his fleet, Michinobu joined with the Minamoto side. He also joined the Battle of Dan-no-Ura."

 #
 # 1180 : Genpei Krieg
 #

 bm_genpeiwar1180:0 "EXTRA - Genpei Krieg"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_desc:0 "Die Taira hatten die Macht in Japan übernommen, sowohl durch Kontakte am Hof als auch durch militärische Gewalt. Kiyomori setzte seinen Enkel Antoku auf den Thron und wurde Regent. Seine Zwangsmaßnahmen führten 1180 zu einer erneuten Verschwörung unter Minamoto no Yorimasa und Prinz Mochihito, die er in der Ersten Schlacht von Uji militärisch niederschlug. Diese Schlacht gilt als erste des Genpei-Krieges.."

 bm_genpeiwar1180_taira_kiyomori:0 "Kiyomori"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_taira_kiyomori_desc:0 "Taira no Kiyomori\n1118-1181\n\nHead of the Taira clan. After the Hōgen and Heiji rebellion, his clan rose rapidly by keeping the Minamoto clan in check. Kiyomori became Daijō-daijin and established power by the Taira clan. As he married his daughter Tokuko to Emperor Takakura, and the Taira clan monopolized officials of the government, they extremely flourished.\n\nIn his later years, however, Kiyomori got caught up in rising ups of the Minamoto clan and died from fever disease. Also, he is known for encouraging trading between Japan and the Song Dynasty of China."
 bm_genpeiwar1180_taira_munemori:0 "Munemori"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_taira_munemori_desc:0 "Taira no Munemori\n1147-1185\n\nA child of Taira no Kiyomori. Munemori succeeded to Kiyomori after his death. Munemori led the Taira clan and fought against the Minamoto clan risen here and there.\n\nAfter the Battle of Dan-no-Ura, Munemori was caught by Minamoto no Yoshitsune and executed."
 bm_genpeiwar1180_harada_tanenao:0 "Tanenao"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_harada_tanenao_desc:0 "Harada Tanenao\nYear of birth and death unknown\n\nOne of the influential officers of the Dazaifu. Tanenao supported the Taira clan's governance of isle of Kyushu.\n\nAlthough he fought against Kikuchi Takanao, who rose up at Kyushu, and Minamoto no Noriyori, who was a member of Yoritomo's army, he lost at the Battle of the Dan-no-Ura and surrender to the Minamoto clan."
 bm_genpeiwar1180_minamoto_yoritomo:0 "Yoritomo"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_minamoto_yoritomo_desc:0 "Minamoto no Yoritomo\n1147-1199\n\nThe first Shogun of the Minamoto Shogunate. Although Yoritomo lost at the Heiji rebellion and was banished to Izu, he accepted a request of Prince Mochihito that Yoritomo uprose his army.\n\nAs Yoritomo extended his power based in Kamakura, he defeated Minamoto no Yoshinaka, the Taira clan, and Northern Fujiwara. Finally, Yoritomo suppressed Japan. He introduced Shugo and Jitō system as fundamentals of the Samurai government. Then he became a Shogun and established his Shogunate."
 bm_genpeiwar1180_minamoto_yoshinaka:0 "Yoshinaka"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_minamoto_yoshinaka_desc:0 "Minamoto no Yoshinaka\n1154-1184\n\nAlso known as Kiso Yoshinaka. Yoshinaka accepted Prince Mochihito's request to raise at Kiso.\n\nYoshinaka defeated the Taira clan at Kurikara Pass, then he occupied Kyoto. Although the Japanese world was divided by three powers; Minamoto no Yoritomo, Yoshinaka, and the Taira clan, Yoshinaka was opposed to ex-Emperor Go-Shirakawa. Finally, Yoshinaka lost and died by Minamoto no Noriyori and Yoshitsune ordered by Yoritomo."
 bm_genpeiwar1180_takeda_nobuyoshi:0 "Nobuyoshi"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_takeda_nobuyoshi_desc:0 "Takeda Nobuyoshi\n1128-1186\n\nA member of the Minamoto clan of Kai. Nobuyoshi accepted Prince Mochihito's request to raise at Kai.\n\nNobuyoshi defeated the Taira army at the Battle of Fujikawa. Thanked of it, Yoritomo gave him an important position. Later Nobuyoshi caught on suspicion of rebellion, which led his child murdered with malice aforethought."
 bm_genpeiwar1180_yamamoto_yoshitsune:0 "Yoshitsune"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_yamamoto_yoshitsune_desc:0 "Yamamoto Yoshitsune\nYear of birth and death unknown\n\nA member of the Minamoto clan at Ōmi. Yoshitsune raised his army corresponding with the Minamoto clan's uprising.\n\nHe entered Kyoto together with Minamoto no Yoshinaka and was in charge of sustaining an order of Kyoto."
 bm_genpeiwar1180_toki_mitsunaga:0 "Mitsunaga"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_toki_mitsunaga_desc:0 "Toki Mitsunaga\nYear of birth and death unknown\n\nA member of the Minamoto clan at Mino. Mitsunaga raised his army corresponding with the Minamoto clan's uprising.\n\nHe entered Kyoto together with Minamoto no Yoshinaka."
 bm_genpeiwar1180_fujiwara_hidehira:0 "Hidehira"
 bm_genpeiwar1180_fujiwara_hidehira_desc:0 "Fujiwara no Hidehira\n1122-1187\n\nHidehira was the third generation of North Fujiwara, leading to the heyday of them.\n\nAt the time of the uprising of Minamoto no Yoritomo, Hidehira was ordered by the Taira clan to defeat Yoritomo but Hidehira acted nothing. After the ruin of the Taira clan, he gave shelter to Minamoto no Yoshitsune who was opposing Yoritomo.\n\nHidehira's body is rested at Chūson-ji Konjiki-dō."

