 #
 # 1560 : Schlacht von Okehazama
 #

 bm_sengoku1560:0 "Schlacht von Okehazama"
 bm_sengoku1560_desc:0 "In den 1540er und 1550er Jahren führten die Clans Imagawa und Oda mehrere Schlachten. Nachdem er (Imagawa Yoshimoto) sich mit Takeda Shingen und Hojo Ujiyasu verbündet hatte, versuchte Imagawa Yoshimoto, diese Rivalität zu beenden und den Weg nach Kyoto zu sichern. 1560 rief er eine massive Armee von über 20.000 Mann an, um Oda Nobunaga zu besiegen, der kürzlich seinen eigenen Clan vereinigt hatte.."

 bm_sengoku1560_oda_nobunaga:0 "Nobunaga"
 bm_sengoku1560_oda_nobunaga_desc:0 "Oda Nobunaga\n1534-1582\n\nNobunaga defeated the Imagawa's army at the Battle of Okehazama. Allied with Tokugawa Ieyasu, Nobunaga destroyed the Saito clan and established a base at Gifu.\n\nWith Ashikaga Yoshiaki, Nobunaga entered Kyoto to install Yoshiaki as a Shogun, later opposed to and banished him. It meant the demise of the Ashikaga Shogunate. Nobunaga defeated Azai and Asakura's army at the Battle of Anekawa, and also the Takeda clan at the Battle of Nagashino.\n\nConstructing the Azuchi castle and voyaging out towards the unification of Japan, however, he got betrayed by Akechi Mitsuhide and died at Honno-ji."
 bm_sengoku1560_imagawa_yoshimoto:0 "Yoshimoto"
 bm_sengoku1560_imagawa_yoshimoto_desc:0 "Imagawa Yoshimoto\n1519-1560\n\nYoshimoto entered into Buddhist priesthood, but returned to the secular life after the death of his brother Terumune and succeeded to him. \n\nYoshimoto conquered Mikawa besides with his original domain, Suruga and Tōtōmi. Yoshimoto is known as \"the best samurai among the Tōkaidō.\""
 bm_sengoku1560_matsudaira_motoyasu:0 "Motoyasu"
 bm_sengoku1560_matsudaira_motoyasu_desc:0 "Matsudaira Motoyasu\n1543-1616\n\nLater Motoyasu changed his name to Tokugawa Ieyasu. He spent his childhood as a hostage to the Imagawa clan and the Oda clan.\n\nAfter the Battle of Okehazama, Motoyasu became independent from the Imagawa clan. At first, he entered a military alliance with Oda Nobunaga, yet the position fell to a vassal gradually.\n\nAfter the death of Nobunaga, Ieyasu (Motoyasu) became a subject to Toyotomi Hideyoshi. After the death of Hideyoshi, Ieyasu won at the Battle of Sekigahara and established the Tokugawa Shogunate."
 bm_sengoku1560_takeda_shingen:0 "Shingen"
 bm_sengoku1560_takeda_shingen_desc:0 "Takeda Shingen\n1521-1573\n\nBanishing his father Nobutora, Shingen became independent. He invaded Shinano then he was opposed to Uesugi Kenshin, fought each other several times at the Battles of Kawanakajima.\n\nShingen joined the anti-Nobunaga Coalition and defeated Tokugawa Ieyasu at the Battle of Mikatagahara, yet Shingen died from illness at his camp.\n\nHe is known as \"the Tiger of Kai.\""
 bm_sengoku1560_nagao_kagetora:0 "Kagetora"
 bm_sengoku1560_nagao_kagetora_desc:0 "Nagao Kagetora\n1530-1578\n\nLater Kagetora changed his name to Uesugi Kenshin.\n\nHe sheltered Murakami Yoshiharu who was defeated by Takeda Shingen, and Uesugi Norimasa who was banished by Hojo Ujiyasu. Kagetora was given the title of Kantō Kanrei and renowned his family name \"Uesugi\" from Norimasa. Kenshin (Kagetora) fought against Shingen over Shinano and Ujiyasu over Kantō.\n\nKenshin is known as \"the God of the War\" or \"the Dragon of Echigo.\" He died right before his expedition."
 bm_sengoku1560_hojo_ujiyasu:0 "Ujiyasu"
 bm_sengoku1560_hojo_ujiyasu_desc:0 "Hojo Ujiyasu\n1515-1571\n\nUjiyasu was the third generation of the Go-Hojo clan and led to the heyday of them.\n\nHe destroyed the Uesugi clan of Ogigayatsu over the great victory of the Siege of Kawagoe Castle. And Ujiyasu exiled Kantō Kanrei Uesugi Norimasa to Echigo.\n\nPerforming Kenchi (land surveying) and reforming the tax system to consolidate the governance of his realm, then he died from the disease after transferring the headship of the family to his child Ujimasa."
 bm_sengoku1560_saito_yoshitatsu:0 "Yoshitatsu"
 bm_sengoku1560_saito_yoshitatsu_desc:0 "Saito Yoshitatsu\n1527-1561\n\nA child of Saito Dosan. Some said that Yoshitatsu was a child of Toki Yorinari.\n\nYoshitatsu succeeded to Dosan who got retirement. They deepened the conflict and then Yoshitatsu destroyed and killed Dosan at the Battle of Nagaragawa.\n\nYoshitatsu died from disease during the severest time that Oda Nobunaga's invasion."
 bm_sengoku1560_azai_hisamasa:0 "Hisamasa"
 bm_sengoku1560_azai_hisamasa_desc:0 "Azai Hisamasa\n?-1573\n\nA child of Azai Sukemasa and a father of Azai Nagamasa.\n\nFor Hisamasa was pushed by the Kyogoku clan and the Rokkaku clan, it is said that Hisamasa wasn't doing well in terms of foreign affairs.\n\nAfter his retirement and giving the headship of the family to Nagamasa, Hisamasa got attacked by the Oda army at his castle Odani-jo, then he committed suicide."
 bm_sengoku1560_asakura_yoshikage:0 "Yoshikage"
 bm_sengoku1560_asakura_yoshikage_desc:0 "Asakura Yoshikage\n1533-1573\n\nAfter the death of the Shogun Ashikaga Yoshiteru, Yoshikage welcomed Yoshiteru's brother Yoshiaki, however, Yoshiaki left him because Yoshikage wasn't ambitious to enter Kyoto.\n\nAt the time Yoshikage got attacked by Nobunaga, who had entered Kyoto, Yoshikage fought against Nobunaga and in cooperation with Yoshikage's allies Azai Nagamasa, Takeda Shingen, and the Hongan-ji Temple.\n\nAfter the loss of the Battle of Anekawa, Yoshikage got attacked his castle Ichijodani-jo, then committed suicide."

 #
 # 1568 : Tenka Fubu
 #

 bm_sengoku1568:0 "Tenka Fubu"
 bm_sengoku1568_desc:0 "Nach der Schlacht von Okehazama verbündete sich Oda Nobunaga mit Matsudaira Motoyasu (später bekannt als Tokugawa Ieyasu) und fiel in Mino ein, der Provinz seines verstorbenen Schwiegervaters. Er eroberte 1567 die gesamte Provinz und verlegte seine Hauptstadt nach Inabayama, dass er in Gifu umbenannte. Gleichzeitig dominierte das politische Chaos den Kinai. Shogun Ashikaga Yoshiteru wurde ermordet und es gab keinen national anerkannten Herrscher. Nobunaga übernahm sein berühmtes Motto 'Tenka Fubu' (Die Welt mit Gewalt regieren) und wartete auf die Gelegenheit, nach Kyoto zu marschieren.."

