 bm_sengoku1568_mori_motonari_desc:0 "Mori Motonari\n1497-1571\n\nMotonari was a vassal of Amago clan, later Ouchi clan.\n\nAfter the rebel led by Sue Harukata against his liege Ouchi Yoshitaka, Motonari defeated Harukata at the Battle of Itsukushima and extended his influence. Motonari also defeated Amago clan and became a great Daimyo who controlled the whole Chugoku region.\n\nHe is famous for the lesson to teach his three sons the importance of unity."
 bm_sengoku1568_chosokabe_motochika:0 "Motochika"
 bm_sengoku1568_chosokabe_motochika_desc:0 "Chosokabe Motochika\n1539-1599\n\nAfter unification of Tosa, Motochika extended his power across the Shikoku.\n\nHe surrendered to Toyotomi Hideyoshi as a result of Hideyoshi's conquest of the Shikoku, yet Motochika got guaranteed the whole country of Tosa. Later, he joined Conquest of the Isle of Kyushu, Conquest of Odawara, and Japanese invasions of Korea.\n\nHe is famous for the governance law \"The 100 Article Code of Chosokabe Motochika.\""
 bm_sengoku1568_otomo_sorin:0 "Sorin"
 bm_sengoku1568_otomo_sorin_desc:0 "Otomo Sorin\n1530-1587\n\nSorin led Otomo clan to its heyday. He held six titles of Shugo (local governer) and Kyushu Tandai.\n\nIn addition to trading with Europeans, Sorin protected and converted to Christianity. His baptismal name was Francisco. He also sent his embassy to Rome.\n\nAfter the defeat against Shimazu clan, Sorin asked Toyotomi Hideyoshi for help."
 bm_sengoku1568_shimazu_yoshihisa:0 "Yoshihisa"
 bm_sengoku1568_shimazu_yoshihisa_desc:0 ""
# bm_sengoku1568_honganji_kennyo:0 "Kennyo"
# bm_sengoku1568_honganji_kennyo_desc:0 "Kennyo\n1543-1592\n\nThe 11th head of the Hongan-ji Temple.\n\nAs Nobunaga entered Kyoto, Kennyo was opposed to Nobunaga. He organized Ikkō-Ikki (uprising of the Buddhist) and allied with the Takeda, Azai, and Asakura clan. Also, he continued the Ishiyama Hongan-ji War with supported by the Mori clan.\n\nThe war had a truce thanked intermeditation by the Emperor Ōgimachi. After the death of Nobunaga, Kennyo was given land at Horikawa, Kyoto, where he rebuilt Hongan-ji Temple."

 #
 # 1575 : Schlacht von Nagashino
 #

 bm_sengoku1575:0 "Schlacht von Nagashino"
 bm_sengoku1575_desc:0 "Oda Nobunaga rettete sich vor der gegen ihn gebildeten Koalition vollständig. Die Asakura und Azai fielen, Shogun Yoshiaki wurde verbannt und der gefährlichste Feind Takeda Shingen starb. Sein Sohn Takeda Katsuyori gab jedoch den Ehrgeiz seines Vaters nicht auf. Mit ihrer starken Kavallerie griff der neue Anführer des Takeda-Clans Nobunagas Verbündeten Tokugawa Ieyasu wiederholt an. Um Takedas Reiter zu besiegen, beschloss Nobunaga, Schusswaffen mit Bedacht einzusetzen.."

